    Aprs avoir lu plusieurs je vous communique mon new 0.11.0 build ou j'ai mis la cration de module la place du package
    et l'association des modules l'excutable

    

    const std = @import("std");


pub fn build(b: *std.Build) void {
    // Standard release options allow the person running `zig build` to select
    // between Debug, ReleaseSafe, ReleaseFast, and ReleaseSmall.
    const target   = b.standardTargetOptions(.{});
    const optimize = b.standardOptimizeOption(.{});

    // zig-src            source projet
    // zig-src/deps       curs/ form / outils ....
    // src_c              source c/c++
    // zig-src/srcgo      source go-lang
    // zig-src/srcgo/lib  lib.so source.h


    // Definition of module

    // data commune
    const dds = b.createModule(.{
      .source_file = .{ .path = "./deps/curse/dds.zig" },
    });
    // console
    const cursed = b.createModule(.{
      .source_file = .{ .path = "./deps/curse/cursed.zig" },
      .dependencies= &.{.{ .name = "dds", .module = dds }},
    });
    // outils
    const utils = b.createModule(.{
      .source_file = .{ .path = "./deps/curse/utils.zig" },
      .dependencies= &.{.{ .name = "dds", .module = dds }},
    });
    // formulaire
    const forms = b.createModule(.{
      .source_file = .{ .path = "./deps/curse/forms.zig" },
      .dependencies= &.{
        .{ .name = "dds",    .module = dds },
        .{ .name = "cursed", .module = cursed },
        .{ .name = "utils",  .module = utils },
      },
    });



    // Building the executable

    const Prog = b.addExecutable(.{
    .name = "Docscurs",
    .root_source_file = .{ .path = "./Docscurs.zig" },
    .target = target,
    .optimize = optimize,
    });

    Prog.addIncludePath("./srcgo/lib");
    Prog.linkLibC();
    Prog.addObjectFile("./srcgo/lib/libregex.so");
    Prog.addModule("dds"   , dds);
    Prog.addModule("cursed", cursed);
    Prog.addModule("utils" , utils);
    Prog.addModule("forms" , forms);

    Prog.install();
}

    ce n'est qu'un exemple pour vous aider faire votre migration vers Zig 0.11.0

    Bonjour ,
    si vous cherchez comment utiliser regex , il n'y a rien sur Zig pour plus amples renseignements, veuillez consulter ce lien regex
    bon voyons les choses pratiquement, car recopier est une chose, mais le fonctionnement en est une autre.

    d'abord le regz.h

    

    #include <regex.h>
#include <stdbool.h>

bool isMatch(regex_t *re, char const *input) {
  regmatch_t pmatch[0];
  return regexec(re, input, 0, pmatch, 0) == 0;

    pas la peine de dclarer :
    const size_t sizeof_regex_t = sizeof(regex_t);
    const size_t alignof_regex_t = alignof(regex_t);
    a) cela ne fonctionne pas et comment se sortir de l pour viter les dbordements.

    

    const std = @import("std");
const re = @cImport({
  @cInclude("regz.h");
});

pub fn isMatch(strVal : [] const  u8, regVal : [] const  u8 ) bool {
  const allocator = std.heap.page_allocator;
  var slice  = allocator.alignedAlloc(u8, @sizeOf(usize),@sizeOf(usize)) catch unreachable;

  const regex = @ptrCast(*re.regex_t, slice);
  defer allocator.free(@ptrCast([*]u8, regex)[0..slice.len]);
  defer re.regfree(regex); // IMPORTANT!!


  const creg = allocator.alloc(u8, regVal.len ,  ) catch unreachable;
  std.mem.copy(u8, creg, regVal);

  if (re.regcomp(regex,@ptrCast([*]u8, creg),re.REG_EXTENDED | re.REG_ICASE) != 0) {
    // TODO: the pattern is invalid
    // display for test
    std.debug.print("error patern {s}\n", .{regVal});
    return false ;
  }

  const cval = allocator.alloc(u8, strVal.len ) catch unreachable;
  std.mem.copy(u8, cval, strVal);

  return re.isMatch(regex, @ptrCast([*]u8, cval));
}

    Zig ne traduit pas correctement la structure regex_t, nous devons donc faire un peu de travail pour initialiser une valeur. Nous pouvons utiliser l'alignedAlloc d'un Allocator pour crer un regex_t, mais nous devons connatre la taille et l'alignement.

    @sizeOf(usize) remplacera const size_t sizeof_regex_t = sizeof(regex_t); en zig const size_t sizeof_regex_t = sizeof(regex_t);

    puis une fois alignement fait, on retombe sur des dclarations de pointer C en zig

    le reste est connu.

    je souhaite que cela vous aide si vous avez besoin de regex, ici, je ne me sers que de match, on peut toffer

    @bientt

    allocator cree de la memoire, allors si on l'utilise plus if faut le detruire. si c'est 1 objet on utilise create/destroy, si c'est plusieur on utilise alloc/dealloc. et si c'est une structure de quelqu'un d'autre ils on probablement init/deinit. cesi est le cas pour arraylist. si tu ne l'utilise plus il faut fair deinit

    

    const al = arraylist(u8).init(allocator);
// code...
al.deinit();

    mais si tu ne la plus besoin a la fin du bloc c'est plus facil et claire de fair defer:

    

    cons al = arraylist(u8).init(allocator);
defer al.deinit();
// code...

    EN-General > / vs @divFloor 6 dc. 2023
    Arya Elfren 00:00

    cizra said:

    https://ziglang.org/documentation/0.11.0/#Table-of-Operators says / only works with comptime-known arguments.

    To be precise it says "Signed integer operands must be comptime-known and positive."

    Most of the examples in that exercism link use u128 or uXX and so aren't signed integers.

    A visual demonstration would be this:

    

    // Unsigned, so this is fine
export fn unsignedDiv(a: u16, b: u16) u16 {
    return a / b;
}

//  Signed but compile time known
export fn signedDivComp() u16 {
    return @as(i16, 5) / 2;
}

// Signed but not compile time known, COMPILE ERROR
export fn signedDiv(a: i16, b: i16) u16 {
    return a / b;
}

    Proof that the first two compile and the last one doesn't: https://godbolt.org/z/98v13347j

    First, the type of a c style null terminated string in zig is [*:0]const u8{}. The :0 is null termination.

    EN-General > opaque vs anyopaque 28 fvr.
    jnordwick 00:37

    What's the difference between *opaque and *anyopaque?

    +
    Arya Elfren 01:40

    anyopaque is as it says, any opaque value. usually used for c interop. opaque {} is useful in zig code as a separate thing. see https://ziglang.org/documentation/master/#opaque

    Basically the below will give a type error as the opaques are unique. whereas an anyopaque parameter will accept any opaque pointer.

    

    const Foo = opaque {};
const Bar = opaque {};

extern fn barf(b: *Bar) void;

fn foodle(f: *Foo)  void {
    bar(f);
}

    It serves a similar purpose to casting to void* in c.

    also, anyopaque is just a type, whereas opaque is a structure, so you can define decls and methods to an opaque {}. e.g. a wrapper for a c api:

    

    extern "lib" fn lib_init_handle() *Handle;

const Handle = opaque {
    pub fn init() @This() {
        return lib_init_handle();
    }
};

// Handle.init()

    EN-General > generating packed from unapcked stuct at comptime 1 mars
    jnordwick 02:12

    https://godbolt.org/z/1anqxq8Mj

    

    const std = @import("std");

const Template = struct {
    a: u8,
    b: u64,
    c: u8,
    d: u32,
};

const TemplateE = extern struct {
    a: u8,
    b: u64,
    c: u8,
    d: u32,
};

const TemplateP = packed struct {
    a: u8,
    b: u64,
    c: u8,
    d: u32,
};


pub fn make_extern(comptime Base: type) type {
    var ti = @typeInfo(Base);
    ti.Struct.layout = .Extern;
    return @Type(ti);
}

const tt = std.builtin.Type;

pub fn make_packed(comptime Base: type) type {
    var ti = @typeInfo(Base);
    const len = ti.Struct.fields.len;
    var sf: [len]tt.StructField = undefined;
    for(0 .. len) |i| {
        sf[i] = ti.Struct.fields[i];
        sf[i].alignment = 0;
    }
    ti.Struct.layout = .Packed;
    ti.Struct.fields = &sf;
    return @Type(ti);
}


pub fn main() void {
    std.debug.print("defined:\n\tauto   = {}\n\textern = {}\n\tpacked = {}\n\n",
        .{@sizeOf(Template), @sizeOf(TemplateE), @sizeOf(TemplateP)},);

    const A = Template;
    const E = make_extern(A);
    const P = make_packed(A);
    std.debug.print("generated:\n\tauto   = {}\n\textern = {}\n\tpacked = {}\n\n",
        .{@sizeOf(A), @sizeOf(E), @sizeOf(P)},);
}
